Load the Data

For this homework, we will use the shark attack data to visualize where the attacks occurred. The data are from: State of California- Shark Incident Database.

sharks <- read_csv("data/SharkIncidents_1950_2022_220302.csv") %>% 
  clean_names() %>% 
  filter(longitude !="NA" & latitude !="NA") %>% # pulling out NA locations
  mutate(longitude = as.numeric(longitude)) # converting longitude to numeric
  1. Use the range of the latitude and longitude to build an appropriate bounding box for your map.
sharks%>%
  select(longitude, latitude)%>%
  summary()
##    longitude         latitude    
##  Min.   :-124.7   Min.   :32.59  
##  1st Qu.:-123.1   1st Qu.:34.04  
##  Median :-122.0   Median :36.70  
##  Mean   :-121.4   Mean   :36.36  
##  3rd Qu.:-119.6   3rd Qu.:38.18  
##  Max.   :-117.1   Max.   :41.56
lat <- c(32.59, 41.56)
log <-c(-124.7, -117.1)
bbox <- make_bbox(log,lat, f=0.03)
  1. Load a map from stamen in a terrain style projection and display the map.
map1 <- get_stadiamap(bbox, maptype="stamen_terrain", zoom= 7)
##   Stadia Maps  Stamen Design  OpenMapTiles  OpenStreetMap contributors.
ggmap(map1)

  1. Build a map that overlays the recorded observations of shark attacks in California.
  ggmap(map1)+
  geom_point(data=sharks, aes(longitude, latitude), size=0.75, color="black", alpha=0.8)+
  labs(x="Longtitude", y="latitude", title="Shark Attcks in California")

  1. Build a map that only shows the fatalities.
sharksf<-sharks %>%
  filter(injury=="fatal")
ggmap(map1)+
  geom_point(data=sharksf, aes(longitude, latitude), size=0.75, color="black", alpha=0.8)+
  labs(x="Longtitude", y="latitude", title="Shark Attcks in California")

  1. Build the same map (fatalities only), but this time make it interactive using leaflet. Also, color the points red.
sharksf%>%
  summarize(lon_min=min(longitude, na.rm = T),
            lon_max=max(longitude, na.rm = T),
            lat_min=min(latitude, na.rm = T),
            lat_max=max(latitude, na.rm = T))
## # A tibble: 1  4
##   lon_min lon_max lat_min lat_max
##     <dbl>   <dbl>   <dbl>   <dbl>
## 1   -124.   -117.    32.9    39.6
lon_min <- -123.7783    
lon_max <- -117.28  
lat_min <- 32.855   
lat_max <- 39.57833
leaflet(sharksf) %>%
  addProviderTiles(providers$Stadia.StamenTerrain) %>%
  addCircleMarkers(
    lng = ~longitude,   
    lat = ~latitude,
    radius = 2,         
    stroke = FALSE,
    color="red",
    fillOpacity = 0.7 
  ) %>%
  
  addScaleBar(position = "bottomleft") %>%
  
  fitBounds(
    lng1 = lon_min, lat1 = lat_min, 
    lng2 = lon_max, lat2 = lat_max  
  )
  1. Which county has the highest number of recorded shark attacks? Make a map that only shows the attacks in this county. (hint: it may help improve the map if you remove duplicate locations, i.e.multiple attacks at the same location.) San Diego have the highest number of recorded shark attacks.
sharks %>%
  select(county, incident_num)%>%
  group_by(county)%>%
  summarize(n_attacks=n_distinct(incident_num, na.rm=TRUE))%>%
  arrange(desc(n_attacks))
## # A tibble: 21  2
##    county          n_attacks
##    <chr>               <int>
##  1 San Diego              24
##  2 San Mateo              19
##  3 Santa Barbara          19

top_county <- sharks %>%
  filter(county=="San Diego")%>%
  distinct(location, .keep_all = TRUE)
top_county%>%
  select(longitude, latitude)%>%
  summary()
